apons-grade fissionable material (plutonium or uranium).  The only way Iraq is going to get that material is if someone ships it in and violates the trade sanctions imposed on Iraq.  That's a very short list of nations, and an even shorter list of nations with fissionable material just &quot;lying around&quot;.  <br>
<br>
Arguably, the threat of chemical and biological weapons is greater, as there was evidence that the Iraqis had them (past tense), and it is this where the bookkeeping fails.  There is currently no evidence that Iraq CURRENTLY has the weapons the US claims it has.  Whether this means those weapons were hidden or whether the Iraqis either a) scrapped those weapons as their storage facilities became too unstable or b) sold those weapons to pay financial debts is unknown.  For all we know, the weapons could have been destroyed years ago.  Evidence either way is lacking.  <br>
<br>
Even if Saddam is hiding weapons, he can't hide them forever.  If inspections find them then we have a chance to remove them without risking the lives of either American soldiers or Iraqi civilians.  If inspectors find evidence that the weapons no longer exist then we can rest easy knowing that the world's policy of containment with a limited bombing campaign will keep such weapons programs halted.<br>
<br>
There's over ten million people in Iraq and hundreds of thousands of soldiers on either side that are depending on a proper decision.  We owe it to them all to give a peaceful solution every chance. <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Humans are the destroyers, be it of themselves or others.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
