<br>
while i have made my views somewhat clear on other points, I completely agree that as of late, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Bush's</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> warmongering and lack of diplomatic tact has so far overstepped the bounds of common sense as to be unbelievable.  But keep in mind what someone else said above - we're as divided in this country as many others, and few people are truely as extreme as Bush.  He is truely a scary individual at this point.<br>
<br>
That having been said, and i mean this with the utmost respect, &quot;european citizens&quot; are probably the last people who should advise anyone about anything vaugely related to war.  I don't really want to get into another knock down drag out like in some previous threads, but I will point out that Europeans are famous for their a) incredibly short memories (forgetting that a great deal of the problems in the middle east, as well as the north-south economic divide in the world is squarely related to their colonial aggressions of the past 100 years (the us has only ever had 1 colony, in the philipines) and their decisions to slaughter the jews/turn a blind eye while jews were being slaughtered thus neccessitating the development of a jewish state far away from europe to protect them from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the europeans</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->) and b) a quite unique (not neccessarily in a good way) perspective on the world on the part of european youth as a result of being brought up under the american security/economic blanket (NATO, Marshall plan aid, economic stability under a fixed dollar-gold standard and so on) and more importantly, under unsustainable welfare states which ensured that the youth of the modern day europe have a radically different perspective on the world than the rest of us stuck in the gritty realist construct of reality.  We see similar phenomenon on the part of South Korean and Japanese youth as well, much to the horror of their parents who have not been sheltered all their lives and realize the true ugliness of the world.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, Europe has the dubious distinction of instigating not one, but <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>two</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the deadliest wars in modern history, as well as an entire host of other crimes against humanity (for instance, french aggression against vietnam, which the US, for less than sound reasons, decided to continue, and more recently and deplorably, French crimes against humanity in Rwanda, where in order to continue the illusion that they are still a big-power, they assisted the Hutu in brutally slaughtering millions of Tutsi civilians during the Rwandan genocide, and then continued their crime by attempting to obfusticate subsequent UN investigations into the incident - I mention the French specifically because they are the most vocal proponents of &quot;peace&quot; in the Iraq issue.  Let us mention nothing of the billions and billions of illicit deals french companies have with the Iraqi dictator to sell black market oil or anthing like that.  Let us furthermore not ask questions of why exactly Butros Gali was suddenly awarded a highly prestigious position at an internationally reknown french charity immediately following the Rwandan genocide.... and so on).<br>
<br>
Furthermore, and perhaps most telling, the europeans have a very infamous tradition of ignoring the bloody obvious until it's too late, preferring instead to cover their eyes and pretend that the world will fix itself.  As the strongest and most damning evidence, I present europe's response (or lack thereof) towards German aggression in the second world war.  Even after Germany had invaded numerous countries, countries like France continued to pretend that everything would be okay if they just &quot;gave it some time&quot;.  This attitude was made all the more ironic by the fact that they had just gotten done fighting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>another</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> world war only a few decades earlier!  Unfortunately, this attitude lasted all the way up until the German army came knocking on the french border.... and the rest, as they say is history.  This is disturbingly similar to the situation now-a-days, when the Europeans want to shut their eyes to the terrorism breeding the middle-east and the weapons of mass destruction being quietly developed under their noses.  How long will it take before they are spurred out of their cowardly complacency and realize that they must act before it's too late?  Will we have to wait until a nuclear bomb explodes in Paris?<br>
<br>
I am not advocating George Bush's warmongering.  I turn on the news with disbelief at the tag team trio of bush powell and rice and their mindnumbingly ignorant alienation of the international world.  However, when I look at the european protesters, I cannot help but to shake my head with the realization that they are just as ignorant as George Dubyah himself.  The world is a complicated place - we should most certainly not be as aggressive or unilateral as bush is driving us to be - but neither should we the ignorant complacent actors that the average european youth would have us be.<br>
<br>
