<br>
Bush's original premise is correct - the middle east is a dangerous breeding ground for terrorists, and those &quot;rogue nations&quot; which support them must be dealt with, pre-emptively if the need be.  This is where I fundamentally disagree with the europeans, most of whom prefer to pretend that if you ask nicely these rogue regimes will simply roll over and &quot;play nice&quot;.  However, while i feel that the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>means</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by which we should deal with those regimes should have a place for pre-emptive military force, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>it should not rely solely upon military force to the exclusion of other options.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
And this is where I feel that Bush has gone horribly awry, for reasons that continue to escape me, and i feel, the rest of the world as well.  The inspections should be allowed to continue, intensified, in fact.  If and when they find something (and they may have to continue for a long time, as Hussein is a master of deception), then at that point coercive options, including military force should be considered.  But for now, I think that Bush should bide his time and exercise a little bit of the diplomatic tact that makes for good presidents.  Also, as an IR student with a specialisation in E.Asia, I am somewhat puzzled by Bush's nonresponse to recent North Korean aggressions, especially given the blatantly terrorist tendencies of their regime...<br>
<br>
also, rocketpig has an excellent point.  While some of Bush's recent actions have been questionable, he has hardly done anything to deserve being compared to adolf hitler.  This is all the more ironic, as I presume that Noemi, who made the original comment, is romanian (from his/her avatar and name).  Romania, as we all know, suffered under the tyrannical rule of Ceausescu until <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>as recently as 1989!!!</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  I think it is safe to say that Bush is nowhere near as &quot;bad&quot; (for lack of a better word) as Ceausescu (ask any romanian who remembers the savagery of this man) and the fact that Ceausescu pales in comparison to the brutality of the Hitler.  Therefore, I think it is a very poor idea to compare bush to hitler.<br>
